ngle formatted-summary user message plus freshly re-read file/skill/plan/tool-delta attachments. For partial compact (`direction: 'from'`), a literal slice of raw original messages is kept verbatim alongside the summary of only the older/newer portion, preserving prompt-cache prefix. `logForDebugging` logs `truePostCompactTokenCount` (the actual resulting context size) vs the trigger threshold so the *next* turn's `shouldAutoCompact` check is anticipated — comment notes the reconstructed context can still exceed threshold and immediately re-trigger (`willRetriggerNextTurn` telemetry field).\n\n=== KEY DIFFERENCES WORTH NOTING FOR LLAME ===\n- opencode: token estimation is 100% heuristic (chars/4), no real tokenizer/API counts anywhere in the compaction path. claude-code prefers **real usage** from the last API response and only estimates the delta since — much more accurate, worth stealing if llame has access to provider usage stats per turn.\n- opencode's `recent` field (verbatim tail) + rolling-summary-of-summary is architecturally the closest match to a \"keep last N turns verbatim + summarize the rest\" design; claude-code's default full-compact throws away everything except the summary (no verbatim tail) unless the user manually triggers partial-compact.\n- Both use a **buffer-token threshold** (fixed token count of headroom), not a percentage-of-window threshold, as the primary trigger — worth matching for predictability across models with wildly different context sizes.\n- claude-code's boundary-marker-in-transcript + logicalParentUuid parent-chain lineage is directly relevant to llame's issue #57 (compaction lineage) — it's essentially a linked-list \"supersedes\" pointer stored as a UUID reference on the marker message, with position-based (not flag-based) supersession for the read-path filter.\n- opencode's separate `SessionContextEpochTable` (baseline_seq) is a distinct concept from the compaction row itself — it's about *system-context* (tools/system pro