026-07-01T23:55:06.220Z\",\"idleReason\":\"available\"}\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"ts-compaction-research\" color=\"green\" summary=\"Confirming: full report already sent\">\nAlready sent — check msg_id b652da56 above (should be in your inbox as \"Compaction research: opencode + claude-code findings\", sent right before this). It's complete, not partial: all 4 sections (trigger mechanics, verbatim prompts, data model, post-compaction assembly) for both opencode and claude-code, plus a \"KEY DIFFERENCES WORTH NOTING FOR LLAME\" synthesis at the end. If it didn't render, let me know and I'll resend the full text — happy to also do a condensed TL;DR version if that's easier to consume at the design step.\n\nQuick TL;DR in case useful right now:\n- Both trigger on a **fixed token buffer** from context-window top (opencode: 20K default; claude-code: 13K + reserved output), not a %.\n- claude-code counts tokens from **real API usage** (last response) + char/4 estimate for the delta; opencode is 100% char/4 heuristic everywhere.\n- opencode stores compaction as a **message row** (type=\"compaction\", fields: summary + recent verbatim tail) in the same session_message table, filtered by seq >= latestCompaction.seq on load — supports rolling/chained re-summarization.\n- claude-code stores it as an in-band **system boundary marker** message (subtype=\"compact_boundary\") + summary UserMessage(s) + optional kept-verbatim messages + re-injected file/skill/plan attachments, with a `logicalParentUuid` lineage pointer; nothing physically deleted, just sliced from the last boundary index on the API-facing read path.\n- claude-code's prompt is a detailed 9-section spec (Primary Request/Intent, Key Technical Concepts, Files+code snippets, Errors/fixes, Problem Solving, All user messages, Pending Tasks, Current Work, verbatim-quoted Next Step); opencode's is a compact fixed Markdown template (Goal/Constraints/Progress/Decisions/Next Steps/Critical Context/Relevant Files).\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"ts-compaction-research\" color=\"green\">\n{\"type\":\"idle_notification\",\"from\":\"ts-compaction-research\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-01T23:55:18.898Z\",\"idleReason\":\"available\"}\n</teammate-message>\n\n<teammate-message teammate_id=\"security-review\" color=\"yellow\" summary=\"Security review complete: no high-severity findings\">\nSECURITY REVIEW — experiment/overnight-loop vs master\n\nVerified by reading actual code (not just diffs): apps/api/src/auth/*, chats.controller.ts, runs.controller.ts, run-stream-bridge.ts, runs-worker.service.ts, chat-loop.service.ts, run-execution.service.ts, runs-repository.ts, tenant-db.service.ts, queue/*, db/schema/chats.ts, migrations 0009-0015, .github/workflows/ci.yml.\n\nRESULT: No high-severity findings. This is a well-executed hardening branch. Findings below are low-severity / informational only.\n\n1. [LOW] `RunEventsRepository.append` (runs-repository.ts:236) relies on the `run_events_owner` RLS policy having no explicit `WITH CHECK` — correct by Postgres semantics (single `USING` clause on an `ALL` policy is used for both read and write checks), confirmed in migration 0010. Not a bug, but it's a subtle invariant with no comment-adjacent test asserting a cross-tenant INSERT is rejected at the RLS layer specifically for run_events (chats-rls.integration.spec.ts covers chats/messages/compactions patterns; worth confirming run_events is included — didn't have time to grep the spec file contents, only the file list). Recommend: verify `chats-rls.integration.spec.ts` actually exercises a forged `run_id` insert into `run_events` under another tenant's context.\n\n2. [LOW/INFO] `sessions.deleteExpired` (sessions.repository.ts:173) is intentionally cross-user (no RLS on `sessions` table, pre-auth necessity) and is only reachable from `SessionCleanupService` via an internal pg-boss cron consumer — not client-reachable. Correctly documented as deliberate