bot: JSON `parts` column; opencode: JSON `SessionMessageData`; open-webui: inline in `content`). Given your run-event log is already the durable record for everything else in a run, persisting reasoning as run-events (and/or a `reasoning` message part, consistent with your \"assistant message currently persists only final text parts\" baseline) is the pattern, not the exception. It also buys resumability for free, matching your worker-based run architecture.\n\n**Strip from next-turn context — confirm what refs do:** Your assumption that stripping is \"the usual practice\" is **not what any of these three do unconditionally**. ai-chatbot re-feeds unconditionally (no filtering logic exists in its `convertToModelMessages` call path). opencode re-feeds *conditionally on same-model*, demoting to plain text on model switch — the more defensible design, and directly reusable: llame already supports per-project/user BYOK across heterogeneous providers, so a model/provider change between turns is a realistic case, and Anthropic extended-thinking signatures in particular are provider/model-bound and will not carry over. Recommendation: mirror opencode — keep reasoning as a structured part in context when the next turn uses the same model+provider (this is required for Anthropic extended thinking with tool use, and is neutral-to-helpful elsewhere); demote to plain text (or drop) when the model changed. Blanket-stripping (open-webui's implicit practice for background tasks) is the safe fallback if you want to ship the minimum viable version first — it's not wrong, just leaves the \"same-model continuity\" optimization on the table.\n\n**Reconciling `agents-best-practices`' \"don't expose hidden reasoning\" with a user-owned RLS-scoped run-event log:** That caveat is about *operational/shared* traces — logs an operator, another tenant, or a downstream automated consumer (another agent, an audit dashboard, a support engineer) could read, where leaking chain-of-thought risks jail